Critical review of the Pillar 1

This section is not applicable because IRRBB does not belong to Pillar 1

Key risk drivers and sensitivities

The earning approach has highlighted a need of capital of 5.7 G€ for the rising rates scenario.
This demonstrates the Group's sensitivity to two combined effects: rising interest rates and widening of BPCE's own credit spread. Two elements that increase refinancing costs (including the effects of customer arbitrage and share remuneration) and carry cost of fixe interest rate position. 

Mutual information between economic and normative perspectives

The normative perspective seeks to quantify the impacts of several adverse scenarios on future profitability (through NII forecasts) and their consequences on the solvency trajectory. The normative perspective is based on the NII sensitivity over the next three years on a dynamic balance sheet. The exercise relies on several internal deterministic scenarios validated by the group’s senior management regarding the evolution of interest rates, liquidity spreads and assets and liabilities outstanding amounts. Assets and liabilities are not deemed constant but vary over time and from one scenario to another. The evolution of the volumes of the different assets and liabilities classes are determined by the budget forecast for the baseline one and by the finance control team for the adverse scenarios. These hypotheses take into account the projected evolution of interest rates, refinancing constraints and probable arbitrage between deposit instruments.
The economic perspective seeks to assess potential financial loss over a 1 year period under a 99.9% confidence level on the part of the balance-sheet which is sensitive to interest rates. As already explained in the section “1.1 Description of the methodology”, this approach consists of two separate sub-perspectives: one in net residual value (compared to equity value) and another one in terms of sensitivity of net income after dividends payed to the shareholders, compared with budget.
The economic approach is based on the same behavioural models and conventions than the normative perspective and is consistent with the assumptions used by the banks for the actual interest rates management. On the other hand, unlike the normative perspective, the economic perspective is fully static for the value approach and implemented under the same December 2024 volume forecasts (regardless the interest rates scenario) for the revenues approach. Moreover, the stressed interest rates of the economic perspective are defined from historical scenarios and not from deterministic scenarios.
	Internal limit system
No internal limits on IRRBB and result are used as part of the risk monitoring and reporting systems based on the ICAAP outcomes under the economic perspective for the risk, or sub-risks, considered in this note.

	System, data and industrialisation

Data used stem from BPCE assets and liabilities management systems:
Risk Confidence ALM (RCO) for BPCE SA and retail banks,
Riskpro for GFS positions.
The calculation process is run under an internal tools (‘PASS ALM’) owned by ALM department. 
To be noted that PASS ALM is the single tool used for all NII (and liquidity) projections and as such for ICAAP economic approach but also for ICAAP normative approach (STI), EBA Stress test and STE calculations.

 
	Control framework
Control outputs

Level 1 controls in place explain the variation between ICAAP exercices. Moreover the consistency of the results is analyzed compared to other exercices (STE,RAF).

Independent validation

As all Group’s models evolution, the methodology for the economic approach of the IRRBB has been submitted to the internal validation (MRM department, within the BPCE’s risk division).
Review and validation have been performed by the group model committee for the end of Q2 2024 and evolution listed above will be controlled and reviewed for 2025 exercise.
 
	Future outlook

Analytical works are still in progress to define how outputs under the economic approach can be used for operational steering of the interest rate risk framework, as of today, capital is required to cover IRRBB at the group level.
	Measure and monitoring at local level Group (calculation by entities to be done, now possible thanks to Pass ALM improvements)
	Possible role of BPCE SA to cover IRRBB in extremely adverse conditions (as it is done for liquidity as BPCE SA is the lender of last resort)
.

 
